          "body": "The indictment of 18:13-17 is one of the most rhetorically powerful passages in the prophetic literature. Yahweh calls the nations as witnesses and frames the indictment as a question of natural order: 'Does the snow of Lebanon forsake the rock of the open country? Or is the cold flowing water from a foreign land ever snatched away?' (18:14). The answer is obvious — of course not. Snow on Hermon does not abandon its mountain; cool streams do not cease their flowing. These are among the most reliable physical constants of the ancient Near East. Against this backdrop of natural faithfulness, Israel's defection is framed as a violation of natural order more shocking than if physics itself broke down. 'My people have forgotten Me' (18:15) — they have done what snow and water never do. The consequence follows the logic of the abandonment: those who chose bypaths over the highway will find their land made desolation, an object of perpetual hissing (18:16), and their God showing His back rather than His face in their day of calamity (18:17). The east wind — the sirocco, the desert wind that withers everything it touches — will scatter them before their enemies."
